et, E.G., Transport of carbon and nitrogen by surface runoff from hillslopes in the Central Coast region of California (2002) J. Environ. Qual., 31, pp. 1207-1213; Florsheim, J.L., Keller, E.A., Best, D.W., Fluvial sediment transport in response to moderate storm flows following chaparral wildfire, Ventura County, southern California (1991) Geol. Soc. Am. Bull., 103, pp. 504-511; Gabet, E.J., Gopher bioturbation: Field evidence for nonlinear hillslope diffusion (2000) Earth Surf. Processes Landforms, 25 (13), pp. 1419-1428; Gabet, E.J., Post-fire thin debris flows: Field observations of sediment transport and numerical modeling (2003) Earth Surf. Processes Landforms, , in press; Gabet, E.J., Sediment transport by dry ravel (2003) J. Geophys. Res., 108 (1 B), p. 2049. , doi:10.1029/2001JB001686; Gabet, E.J., Dunne, T., Landslides on coastal sage-scrub and grassland hillslopes in a severe El Niño winter: The effects of vegetation conversion on sediment delivery (2002) Geol. Soc. Am. Bull., 114 (8), pp. 983-990; Gabet, E.J., Dunne, T., Sediment detachment by rainpower (2003) Water Resour. Res., 39 (1), p. 1002. , doi:10.1029/2001WR000656; Gabet, E.J., Reichman, O.J., Seabloom, E., The effects of bioturbation on soil processes and sediment transport (2003) Annu. Rev. Earth Planet. Sci., 31, pp. 259-273; Giorgi, F., Brodeur, F.S., Bates, G.T., Regional climate change scenarios over the United States produced with a nested regional climate model (1994) J. Clim., 7 (3), pp. 375-399; Hibbert, A.R., Increases in streamflow after converting chaparral to grass (1971) Water Resour. Res., 7 (1), pp. 71-80; Horton, J.S., Kraebel, C.J., Development of vegetation after fire in the chamise chaparral of southern California (1955) Ecology, 36 (2), pp. 244-262; Houghton, J., Callander, B., Varney, S., (1992) Climate Change 1992: The Supplementary Report to the IPCC Scientific Assessment, 199p. , Cambridge Univ. Press, New York; Iida, T., A stochastic hydro-geomorphological model for sh